<h2 id="Problem-Definition"><strong>Problem Definition</strong><a class="anchor-link" href="#Problem-Definition"> </a></h2><p>We will use <a href="https://fenicsproject.org/">FEniCS</a> to solve the elasticity differential equations. The problem involves a 2D beam as described below</p>
<p><img src="/blog/images/copied_from_nb/images/problem_diagram.png" alt="problem diagram"></p>
<p>subject to the elasticity equations</p>
<p>{% raw %}
$$ \mathrm{\mathbf{Kinematics:}}\;\;\;\; \epsilon = \frac{1}{2} \left( \nabla u + \nabla u^{T} \right) \;\; \mathrm{in}\; \Omega$$
{% endraw %}
{% raw %}
$$ \mathrm{\mathbf{Force\;equilibrium:}}\;\;\;\; \nabla \mathbf{\sigma}=0 \;\; \mathrm{in}\; \Omega$$
{% endraw %}
$$ \mathrm{\mathbf{Constitutive \;Law:}}\;\;\;\; \mathbf{\sigma} = \lambda \mathrm{tr}(\mathbf{\epsilon})\mathbb{1}+2\mu\mathbf{\epsilon} \;\; \mathrm{in}\; \Omega$$</p>
<p>with the boundary conditions</p>
<p>{% raw %}
$$ u=0 \;\; \mathrm{on}\; \partial \Omega_{\mathrm{fixed}} $$
{% endraw %}
{% raw %}
$$ F_x=400 \; \mathrm{N/mm} \;\; \mathrm{on}\; \partial \Omega_{\mathrm{load}} $$
{% endraw %}
{% raw %}
$$ F_y=800 \; \mathrm{N/mm} \;\; \mathrm{on}\; \partial \Omega_{\mathrm{load}} $$
{% endraw %}</p>
<p>where $u$ is the unknown displacement in the domain $\Omega$, $\epsilon$ is the strain, $\sigma$ is the stress, and $\lambda$ and $\mu$ are the material <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lam%C3%A9_parameters">Lame parameters</a> that can be obtained from the Young's modulus $E$ and Poisson's ratio $\nu$.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

We found that creating a <a href="https://docs.conda.io/en/latest/">conda</a> environment and installing <code>mshr</code> via conda is the easiest way.</p>

</div>

<span class="n">nu</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">0.3</span> <span class="c1"># Poisson&#39;s ratio</span>

<h3 id="Geometry-and-mesh"><em>Geometry and mesh</em><a class="anchor-link" href="#Geometry-and-mesh"> </a></h3><p>In order to generate the beam geometry, we need to use <code>mshr</code> since the built-in meshes in FEniCS only include basic geometries. We initially create a rectangle with the overall dimensions of the beam and then subtract the void regions.</p>

            <span class="n">Point</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">length</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">height</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="n">geom</span> <span class="o">-=</span> <span class="n">Rectangle</span><span class="p">(</span>
            <span class="n">Point</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">channel_size</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">3</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">channel_size</span><span class="p">),</span>
            <span class="n">Point</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">channel_size</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">4</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">channel_size</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">ch_x</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">2.5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">length</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">geom</span> <span class="o">-=</span> <span class="n">Rectangle</span><span class="p">(</span>

<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">ch_x</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">2.5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">length</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">):</span>

<h3 id="Finite-element-function-space-and-functions"><em>Finite element function space and functions</em><a class="anchor-link" href="#Finite-element-function-space-and-functions"> </a></h3><p>Now that we have a mesh, we define the solution space <code>V</code> as a vector function bounded by second-degree <a href="http://femwiki.wikidot.com/elements:lagrange-elements">Lagrange</a> elements. The trial function <code>du</code>, test function <code>v</code>, and solution function <code>u</code> belong to the solution space <code>V</code> and will later be used during the variational formulation of the problem.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">V</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">VectorFunctionSpace</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mesh</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;Lagrange&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c1"># quadradic elements</span>
<span class="n">du</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">TrialFunction</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">V</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">u</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Function</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">V</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">name</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;Displacement&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">v</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">TestFunction</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">V</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Boundary-conditions"><em>Boundary conditions</em><a class="anchor-link" href="#Boundary-conditions"> </a></h3><p>We specify the location of all boundary conditions with <a href="https://github.com/lssr/blog/blob/master/_notebooks/region_selector_2d.py">Region Selector</a>, a small library to select different region types in FEniCS.</p>
<p>Also, we create a <code>MeshFunction</code>to assign arbitrary positive integers to 1 dimensional elementsto create mesh subdomains. For example, by marking <code>bc_fixed_lower</code> and <code>bc_fixed_upper</code> with a value of <code>1</code>, I can now use <code>ds(1)</code> as a way to specify operations applicable only to the fixed boundary regions. In addition, operations using <code>ds(2)</code> will only apply to the loading region.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">bc_fixed_height</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">0.5</span>

<span class="n">bc_fixed_lower</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">rs</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">GetLinearBoundary</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">from_points</span><span class="p">(</span>
                                            <span class="n">Point</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">),</span>
                                            <span class="n">Point</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">bc_fixed_height</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">bc_fixed_upper</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">rs</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">GetLinearBoundary</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">from_points</span><span class="p">(</span>
                                            <span class="n">Point</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">height</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">bc_fixed_height</span><span class="p">),</span>
                                            <span class="n">Point</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">height</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">load_region</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">rs</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">GetLinearBoundary</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">from_points</span><span class="p">(</span>
                                        <span class="n">Point</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">f_pos_x</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mf">0.4</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">f_pos_y</span><span class="p">),</span>
                                        <span class="n">Point</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">f_pos_x</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mf">0.4</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">f_pos_y</span><span class="p">))</span>


<span class="n">boundaries</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">MeshFunction</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;size_t&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">mesh</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">mesh</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">topology</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dim</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">boundaries</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_all</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">bc_fixed_lower</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mark</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">boundaries</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">bc_fixed_upper</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mark</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">boundaries</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">load_region</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mark</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">boundaries</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ds</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Measure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;ds&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">domain</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">mesh</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">subdomain_data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">boundaries</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">bc_1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">DirichletBC</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">V</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Constant</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">)),</span> <span class="n">bc_fixed_lower</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">bc_2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">DirichletBC</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">V</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Constant</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">)),</span> <span class="n">bc_fixed_upper</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">bc</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">bc_1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">bc_2</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="n">load</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Constant</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">f_x</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">f_y</span><span class="p">))</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Material-model"><em>Material model</em><a class="anchor-link" href="#Material-model"> </a></h3><p>The material model is a simple linear elastic isotropic model. The <code>linear_material_model</code> class takes as arguments the elastic modulus $E$ and Poisson's ratio $\nu$ since both of them are more popular in material datasheets.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">class</span> <span class="nc">linear_material_model</span><span class="p">():</span>
    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="fm">__init__</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">E</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">nu</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">E</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">E</span>
        <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">nu</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">nu</span>
        <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mesh_dim</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mesh</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">topology</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dim</span><span class="p">()</span>

    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">get_lame_constants</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="n">mu</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">E</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">2.0</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">1.0</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">nu</span><span class="p">))</span>
        <span class="n">lmbda</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">E</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">nu</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="p">((</span><span class="mf">1.0</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">nu</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">1.0</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mf">2.0</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">nu</span><span class="p">))</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">lmbda</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">mu</span>

    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">eps</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">u</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">sym</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">grad</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">u</span><span class="p">))</span>

    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">sigma</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">u</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="n">lmbda</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">mu</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_lame_constants</span><span class="p">()</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">lmbda</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">tr</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">eps</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">u</span><span class="p">))</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">Identity</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mesh_dim</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mf">2.0</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">mu</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">eps</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">u</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">mm</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">linear_material_model</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">E</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">nu</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Variational-problem-and-solution"><em>Variational problem and solution</em><a class="anchor-link" href="#Variational-problem-and-solution"> </a></h3><p>The variational formulation in mechanics is better explained in <a href="https://fenicsproject.org/pub/tutorial/html/._ftut1008.html">this FEniCS tutorial</a>. 
In essence, the elasticity differential equations reduce to</p>
<p>{% raw %}
$$ a(du,v) = L(v) $$
{% endraw %}
where
{% raw %}
$$ a(du,v) = \int_{\Omega} \sigma(du):\epsilon(v) \mathrm{d}x $$
{% endraw %}
{% raw %}
$$ L(v) = \int_{\Omega}f \cdot v \mathrm{d}x + \int_{\partial\Omega}T\cdot v \mathrm{d}s $$
{% endraw %}
with $du$ as the trial function, $v$ as the test function, $f$ as the body forces, and $T$ as the traction forces.</p>
<p>In the elastic regime, this formulation can be viewed as conservation of energy. The internal work, $a(du,v)$, must be equal to the external work $L(v)$.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">a</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">inner</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mm</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sigma</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">du</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">mm</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">eps</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">v</span><span class="p">))</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">dx</span>
<span class="n">L</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">dot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">load</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">v</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">ds</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c1"># no body forces</span>
<span class="n">solve</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">a</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="n">L</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">u</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">bc</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
